  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. Some key requirements include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identity\n- Assessing customer risk profiles\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Suspicious Activity Reporting (SAR)\n- Identifying and reporting suspicious transactions\n- Filing reports with financial crime enforcement agencies\n- Monitoring unusual financial patterns\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Implementing internal control systems\n- Conducting employee training\n- Regular risk assessments\n- Maintaining compliance documentation\n\n4. Regulatory Reporting\n- Submitting Currency Transaction Reports (CTRs)\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Cooperating with law enforcement investigations\n\n5. International Regulations\n- Complying with international standards like FATF recommendations\n- Following cross-border transaction guidelines\n- Participating in global information sharing networks\n\nFinancial institutions that fail to meet these obligations can face significant legal penalties, including substantial fines and potential criminal charges.\n\nThese requirements are designed to prevent financial crimes like money laundering, terrorist financing, and other illicit financial activities.",
